         <div type="edition" xml:lang="pra-Latn" rendition="class:83225 maturity:83209">
             <p><lb n="1"/>Utaramitāya dāna<unclear>ṁ</unclear> puphagahan<unclear>i</unclear> v<supplied reason="lost">i</supplied>s<supplied reason="lost">a</supplied>y<supplied reason="lost">i</supplied></p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
             <listApp>
                 <app loc="1">
                     <lem>dāna<unclear>ṁ</unclear></lem>
                     <rdg source="bib:Nakanishi+Hinuber2014_01">dānam</rdg>
                 </app>
             </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:vito">
             <p>A <foreign>pupphagahani</foreign>: the gift of Uttaramittā. Twenty.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
             <p>On the problematic last word, which in light of <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00022.xml">KnI 22</ref>, seems to be a number, see <bibl><ptr target="bib:Nakanishi+Hinuber2014_01"/><citedRange unit="page">46</citedRange></bibl>. Note that the supposed third instance of a number (<foreign>panāsa</foreign>, “fifty”) on the <foreign>pupphagahani</foreign> bearing <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00044.xml">KnI 44</ref> has now proved unsupported. It seems to me unlikely that both numbers in <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00021.xml">KnI 21</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00022.xml">22</ref> serve as location markers, and I would rather interpret this as indicating a length of the object given. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Nakanishi+Hinuber2014_01"/></bibl> assert that the length of the <foreign>pupphagahani</foreign> is uniform, but this is contradicted by the observation of the objects in question. That bearing bearing <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00021.xml">KnI 21</ref> does seems unusually long, so this may have justified this mention.<!--TO ENCODE AS INVISIBLE NOTE: The decoration of the pupphagahani, which is broken preserves eighteen miniature railings, and it is plausible that it had originally twenty.--></p>
         </div>
